  },
  {
    "text": "st hidden layer with nvar−1 neuronsz the second with\nnvary 10 neuronsz and the third with 3 neurons.\nWhen building a network two rules should be kept in mind. The ﬁrst is the theorem by Weierstrassz\nwhich if applied to neural netsz ascertains that for a multilayer perceptron a single hidden layer is\nsuﬃcient to approximate a given continuous correlation function to any precisionz provided that a\nsuﬃciently large number of neurons is used in the hidden layer. If the available computing power",
    "metadata": {
      "source": "data\\Multivariate analysis.pdf",
      "chunk_index": 40
    }
  },
  {
    "text": "t a\nsuﬃciently large number of neurons is used in the hidden layer. If the available computing power\nand the size of the training data sample su ﬃcez one can increase the number of neurons in the\nhidden layer until the optimal performance is reached.\n8svu Artiﬁcial Neural Networks (nonlinear discriminant analysis) 97\nIt is likely that the same performance can be achieved with a network of more than one hidden",
    "metadata": {
      "source": "data\\Multivariate analysis.pdf",
      "chunk_index": 41
    }
