  },
  {
    "text": "ties : performance\n-Many classiﬁers can be trained in one shot\n-Useful for performance comparison\n40\nAdvantages and drawbacks of\ndifferent classiﬁers\nFrom TMVA manual\n41\n126 10 Which MVA method should I use for my problem?\nMV A M ETHOD\nCRITERIA Cuts Likelip\nhood\nPDEp\nRS r\nkpNN\nPDEp\nFoam\nHp\nMatrix\nFisher\nr LD\nMLP BDT Rulep\nFit\nSVM\nPerforp\nNo or linear\ncorrelations\n￿ ￿￿ ￿ ￿ ￿ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿ ￿￿ ￿\nmance Nonlinear\ncorrelations\n◦◦ ￿￿ ￿￿ ◦◦ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿￿\nTraining ◦ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿ ◦ ￿ ◦\nSpeed",
    "metadata": {
      "source": "data\\Multivariate analysis.pdf",
      "chunk_index": 224
    }
  },
  {
    "text": "￿ ￿￿ ￿\nmance Nonlinear\ncorrelations\n◦◦ ￿￿ ￿￿ ◦◦ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿￿\nTraining ◦ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿ ◦ ￿ ◦\nSpeed\nResponse ￿￿ ￿￿ ◦ ￿ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿ ￿￿ ￿\nRobustp Overtraining ￿￿ ￿ ￿ ￿ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿ ◦ ￿ ￿￿\nness Weak variables ￿￿ ￿ ◦◦ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿ ￿￿ ￿ ￿\nCurse of dimensionality ◦ ￿￿ ◦◦ ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿ ￿ ￿\nTransparency ￿￿ ￿￿ ￿ ￿ ￿￿ ￿￿ ◦◦◦◦\nT able 6: Assessment of MV A method propertiesq The symbols stand for the attributes “good” k ￿￿lo “fair”",
    "metadata": {
      "source": "data\\Multivariate analysis.pdf",
      "chunk_index": 225
    }
  },
  {
    "text": "e 6: Assessment of MV A method propertiesq The symbols stand for the attributes “good” k ￿￿lo “fair”\nk￿l and “bad” k ◦lq “Curse of dimensionality” refers to the “burden” of required increase in training statistics\nand processing time when adding more input variablesq See also comments in the textq The FDA method is\nnot listed here since its properties depend on the chosen functionq\n10 Which MVA method should I use for my problem?",
    "metadata": {
      "source": "data\\Multivariate analysis.pdf",
      "chunk_index": 226
    }
  },
  {
    "text": "since its properties depend on the chosen functionq\n10 Which MVA method should I use for my problem?\nThere is obviously no generally valid answer to this questionq To guide the usero we have attempted\na coarse assessment of various MV A properties in Table yq Simplicity is a virtueo but only if it is not\nat the expense of signiﬁcant loss of discrimination powerq Robustness with respect to overtraining\ncould become an issue when the training sample is scarceq Some methods require more attention",
    "metadata": {
      "source": "data\\Multivariate analysis.pdf",
      "chunk_index": 227
    }
  },
  {
    "text": "aining\ncould become an issue when the training sample is scarceq Some methods require more attention\nthan others in this regardq For exampleo boosted decision trees are particularly vulnerable to\novertraining if used without careq 37 To circumvent overtraining a problempspeciﬁc adjustment of\nthe pruning strength parameter is requiredq\nTo assess whether a linear discriminant analysis kLDAl could be su ﬃcient for a classiﬁcation krep",
    "metadata": {
      "source": "data\\Multivariate analysis.pdf",
      "chunk_index": 228
    }
  },
  {
    "text": "q\nTo assess whether a linear discriminant analysis kLDAl could be su ﬃcient for a classiﬁcation krep\ngressionl problemo the user is advised to analyse the correlations among the discriminating variables\nkamong the variables and regression targetl by inspecting scatter and proﬁle plots kit is not enough\nto print the correlation coe ﬃcientso which by deﬁnition are linear onlylq Using an LDA greatly\nreduces the number of parameters to be adjusted and hence allow smaller training samplesq It",
    "metadata": {
      "source": "data\\Multivariate analysis.pdf",
      "chunk_index": 229
    }
  },
  {
    "text": "greatly\nreduces the number of parameters to be adjusted and hence allow smaller training samplesq It\nusually is robust with respect to generalisation to larger data samplesq For moderately intricate\nproblemso the function discriminant analysis kFDAl with some added nonlinearity may be found\nsuﬃcientq It is always useful to crosspcheck its performance against several of the sophisticated\nnonlinear methods to see how much can be gained over the use of the simple and very transparent\nFDAq\n37",
    "metadata": {
      "source": "data\\Multivariate analysis.pdf",
      "chunk_index": 230
    }
  },
  {
    "text": "linear methods to see how much can be gained over the use of the simple and very transparent\nFDAq\n37\nHowever, experience shows that the BDT performance is amazingly robust – even for strongly overtrained decision\ntrees.\nExercises\n- Problem inspired by Higgs searches in H->2photons channel at LHC\n-Goal : be able to estimate the sensitivity of a search for a small peak over a\nhuge background, using multivariate methods\n-3 exercises :\n-Setting up Root and TMVA environment, TMVA basics",
    "metadata": {
      "source": "data\\Multivariate analysis.pdf",
      "chunk_index": 231
    }
  },
  {
    "text": "ground, using multivariate methods\n-3 exercises :\n-Setting up Root and TMVA environment, TMVA basics\n-Using a MVA method inside the analysis\n-Estimation of analysis sensitivity\n42",
    "metadata": {
      "source": "data\\Multivariate analysis.pdf",
